explanation:
- UT_StubTableEntry_t (full definition): The function writes into StubPtr->Data.Rvc and directly assigns StubPtr->Data.Rvc.Buf.IndirectPtr = ValuePtr. To check for a const-qualification violation we must know the exact declared type of IndirectPtr (e.g. void * vs const void *). The struct also shows whether other members (TypeName, etc.) are const-qualified.
- Type of Data.Rvc.Buf (e.g. UT_RetvalBuffer_t) and its member IndirectPtr: If the Buf type is a separate typedef/struct, provide its declaration so the analyzer can see the pointer member type, because the const-qualification question centers on that member.
- UT_StoreRetval (function prototype): The alternative branch calls UT_StoreRetval(&StubPtr->Data.Rvc.Buf, ValuePtr, ...). The prototype shows how the buffer parameter is used and whether it expects/produces any non-const pointer conversions; it also shows whether ValuePtr is accepted as const void * or coerced, which affects whether const is propagated or cast away.
- UT_ValueGenre_t (enum) and UT_ValueGenre_OPAQUE (constant): The control flow (store pointer vs copy) depends on this enum value. The semantic meaning of OPAQUE (and any other genres) is required to know when a pointer is intentionally stored as-is and whether that implies keeping it const.
- UT_GetStubEntry (function prototype): The function returns the StubPtr used for assignments. The prototype reveals the exact return type (e.g. UT_StubTableEntry_t * vs const UT_StubTableEntry_t *) and whether any implicit constness is involved in how the returned pointer will be used/modified.

Providing these symbols (full declarations/prototypes) lets the next analyzer determine if any assignment or call in UT_ConfigureGenericStubReturnValue discards const qualification or otherwise violates the MISRA guideline that pointers should point to const-qualified types when possible.
